    <note>Shi(1) Ji [7330]  In 1112, he ranked # 1 on the local exam (xianggong) and subsequently received the jinshi. He did not cooperate with Cai(1) Jing [1649] and was relegated to minor posts until the Southern Song. Fan(2) Xiaochun's [7215] father-in-law. Ji's cousin Minzhan's [3720] son-in-law, Fan(2) Zhonggu [3277], has the same generational name as all the great grandsons and great grandnephews of Fan(2) Bailu [578]. According to Chao(2) Gongsu, Ji's 8th generation ancestor, Zheng [13897], moved to Meizhou, Yangwu from Pingyuan jun (Dezhou, Pingyuan county), which was a Shi(1) choronym, at the end of Tang. According to Wei(5) Liaoweng [4001], the lineage traced its ancestry to the Tang official, Shi(1) Yuanxi, whose son, Di [13898], moved to Pengshan for the first time. My guess is that Zheng and Yuanxi are the same person (therefore, Yuanxi not in dataset), who moved to Meizhou, Meishan county, and that Di was the first to move to Pengshan. This would be consistant with the identification of Shi(1) Gu [3719] (a Meizhou, Meishan resident), the father-in-law of Sun(1) Xisou's [1529] grandson, Jun [3773], as a member of Ji's lineage. Chao Gongsu, WJ, 52.1a-3a; SS, 460.8a; Wei Liaoweng, WJ, 87.5b-8b. CBD, 3, 2046.</note>
